recordings.rmk: This recording was made using an AudioMoth autonomous recording unit , left in a southeastern U.S. saltmarsh where the dominant vegetation is Spartina alterniflora for 3 days to record from 0500 to 0800 each day. The birds expected to be found inhabiting in the saltmarsh at this time of year are: Seaside Sparrow, Saltmarsh Sparrow, Clapper Rail, Red-winged Blackbird, Palm Warbler, Yellow-rumped (Myrtle) Warbler, Eastern Marsh Wren and a variety of shorebirds on the exposed shell beaches and mud exposed by the tides, as well as common wading birds. Recording the sparrows in an undisturbed environment was the primary goal.

recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk: A flock of migrating Palm Warblers in a screen of trees between a golf course and a weedy field.  Most were well hidden in the tree, but two or three ventured out to verify their identification.  They will move on through, although a few will stay to spend much of the usually mild winter months both here and in the nearby salt marsh.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Approached and perched ~3m above the ground in shrubby vegetation, calling apparently at me. This bird wintered at this location, rare for the area. Seen several times through February 2016.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#
No edits

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
